cs.CV, cs.MM, cs.IT, cs.HC, cs.GR

This paper proposes a new full reference IQA model for image and video processing, which involves the use of gradient similarity, chromaticity similarity, and deviation pooling. These techniques are commonly used in computer vision and multimedia communication, which suggests that cs.CV and cs.MM are likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the formulation and calculation of these techniques, which involves mathematical and statistical methods, indicating that cs.IT is another possible sub-category. Additionally, the proposed model aims to model the human visual system, which suggests that cs.HC may also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper presents experimental results on various datasets, which suggests that cs.GR (graphics) may also be a relevant sub-category.
